artment and An Garda Síochána.  The strategy recognises the need for a balanced health-led approach - reducing demand, while also reducing access to illegal drugs - and is aimed at reducing the number of people criminalised for the possession of drugs for personal use.\n\nThe national drug strategy, Reducing Harm, Supporting Recovery, sets out government policy on drug and alcohol use for the period 2017 to 2025. The strategy provides an integrated health-led approach to drug and alcohol use, focused on reducing the harms for individuals, families and communities and promoting rehabilitation and recovery. The vision of Reducing Harm, Supporting Recovery is for a healthier and safer Ireland.\n\nThis strategy represents a whole of Government response to drug and alcohol use in Ireland. This Government is acutely aware of the sustained and significant damage that the importation and use of illicit drugs has on communities right across the country and that it funds organised crime. Every effort is made to combat not just the importation of illicit drugs but also firearms, ammunition and cash that inevitably accompany this very serious organised criminal activity.", :token-overlap-p-by-sentence [0.8888888888888888 0.8 0.7727272727272727 0.9 0.7368421052631579 0.6666666666666666], :answer "The government is implementing the National Drugs Strategy 2017-2025, titled \"Reducing Harm, Supporting Recovery,\" which represents a whole-of-Government response to drug and alcohol use in Ireland. This strategy takes a health-led approach while also working to reduce access to illegal drugs.\n\nThe implementation is led by the Minister for Health and the Minister of State with responsibility for Public Health, Wellbeing and the National Drugs Strategy, with actions assigned to various stakeholders including the Department of Justice and An Garda Síochána.\n\nThe strategy aims to reduce harm for individuals, families and communities while promoting rehabilitation and recovery. It seeks to balance reducing demand for drugs with limiting access to illegal drugs, and includes efforts to reduce the number of people criminalised for possession of drugs for personal use.\n\nRevenue also plays a key role through its drugs interdiction strategy, which supports the government's approach by focusing on prevention, detection, interception and seizure of controlled drugs that might be smuggled into or out of Ireland.", :cosine-similarity 0.8655469622307834, :bleu-faithfulness 3.285984294827762E-5, :rouge-l-f1 0.22727272429752068} {:metric-llm-faithfulness-explanation "{\n  \"reasoning\": \"Each point in the statement is explicitly supported by the context: 1) the context cites over €211 million under the 2019 GP Agreement for fees, supports, and new services; 2) it notes measures to increase the number of GPs to improve access; 3) it confirms the Department and HSE have commenced a Strategic Review with stakeholder input to examine GP capacity and recommend sustainable measures; 4) it specifies that underserved rural and urban deprived areas and ways to attract GPs there will be examined; 5) it mentions a programme to quickly improve access, especially in limited‐access areas; and 6) it states that upon completion of the review a paper will outline findings and recommended actions.\",\n  \"score\": \"Yes\"\n}", :rouge-l-recall 0.7272727272727273, :flesch-kincaid-grade-level 13.118529411764708, :flesch-reading-ease 26.241715686274546, :rouge-faithfulness 0.6666666666666666, :retrieved-context ["Following it's completion a paper is to be presented to me outlining the findings of the review and setting out recommended actions to respond to the identified findings.  It is worth noting that the Government has undertaken measures to increase GP capacity and improved access to services. Increased annual investment of over €211 million was provided for under the 2019 GP Agreement, providing for increased GP fees, supports and new services." "The Government is awar